   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <gap reason="omitted" extent="unknown"/>ci <choice>
                  <sic>bibas</sic>
                  <corr>vivas</corr>
               </choice> cum eulogia conp<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">are</supplied>
               <gap reason="lost" extent="unknown"/>
            </ab>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>May you live with equal blessing.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>This bowl-fragment is a rare example of the gold-glasses found in the catacombs where
                    they served as grave-markers. Gold glasses were common in 3rd-4th century Rome,
                    where this bowl's elaborate technique supports dating it to the 4th century.
                    The meaning of the inscription is dubious; "bibas" (may you drink) or an
                    alternative spelling for "vivas" (may you live) that attests for a phonetic
                    development indicated by other Jewish inscriptions. Likewise, the word "eulogia"
                    can refer to the Greek word for "blessing" or to a feminine private name. </p>
         </div>
